loc: Bacan; nr Mount Sibela Peak; North Maluku
rmk: Presumably the same bird as XC202399;  XC202400. Playback was used about 15 minutes before these vocalisations were recorded. Although the bird was not actually seen calling; a megapode-type bird was seen approaching in dense vegetation and making the clucking calls; followed shortly afterwards by the song. Based on the brief view and the fact that this is nothing like Dusky Scrubfowl; this recording must surely be Moluccan Megapode. They were seen in the forest elsewhere on the mountain.

This bird was in the mangroves; calling about an hour after dark. Although not seen; identification was made by comparison with another recordings of Black Bittern (from Australia) and discussion with others who have heard this at the same locality. The sonograms are almost identical. Originally thought to possibly be a scops owl. [Subspecies here most likely australis] Same bird as XC202691; XC202692; XC202693.

This mystery recording is from a mature mangrove woodland (approximately at S 8°23'20.95" // E 124°06'38.94").  It sounds like a Scops-owl to me but I failed to see it. The forest area was almost impossible to access (mangroves) adjacent to eucalypt woodland and I had no luck with playback. The calls sound however different then Otus magics tempestatis which occurs on nearby Flores and Lembata (Lomblen). But no Scops-owl is known from Pantar island; only a Ninox (Ninox [novaeseelandiae] plesseni is present (unlike Flores and Lembata where there is no Ninox).   I heard these calls from more then one location and on subsequent nights.  Peter Collaerts and friends also went to the same location and heard the same calls many months later (but also failed to locate and visually observe it - so a challenge remains...).

id: I had posted this recording earlier on Xeno-Canto but it has gone missing when Xeno-Canto transferred to the new server.  All comments / thoughts remain wellcome.  Anyone wishing to visit Pantar to check out these calls can contact me !
